UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 AN ACT relating to the establishment of the Office of Public Defense.
2 WHEREAS, the General Assembly finds and declares that the Second Amendment
3 to the United States Constitution declares that "A well regulated Militia, being necessary
4 to the security of a free State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be
5 infringed"; and
6 WHEREAS, in District of Columbia v. Heller, 554 U.S. 570 (2008), the United
7 States Supreme Court explained that the Second Amendment's prefatory Militia Clause
8 announces the Amendment's purpose and serves a clarifying function as to the
9 Amendment's protections. To that end, the Second Amendment guarantees the people's
10 unrestricted access to arms to repel invasions and suppress insurrections, render large
11 standing armies unnecessary, and resist tyranny; and
12 WHEREAS, the Supreme Court explained that "the people" protected by the
13 Second Amendment "unambiguously refers to all members of the political community,
14 not an unspecified subset," and presumptively extends to "all Americans"; and
15 WHEREAS, the Supreme Court further explained that the original meaning of the
16 term "Arms" used in the Second Amendment includes "weapons of offence, or armour of
17 defence";"any thing that a man wears for his defence, or takes into his hands, or useth in
18 wrath to cast at or strike another"; and at a minimum, "all firearms"; and thus, the
19 Supreme Court explained, "the Second Amendment extends, prima facie, to all
20 instruments that constitute bearable arms, even those that were not in existence at the
21 time of the founding"; and
22 WHEREAS, the Framers understood the Second Amendment to guarantee
23 armament parity between the American citizen and government infantryman. In 1788,
24 Tench Coxe explained that "Congress have no power to disarm the militia. Their swords,
25 and every terrible implement of the soldier, are the birth-right of an American." Likewise,
26 Henry Campbell Black later explained that "the 'arms' here meant are those of a soldier.
27 ...The citizen has at all times the right to keep arms of modern warfare."; and
Page 1 of 31
XXXX 2/25/2026 1:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 WHEREAS, in addition to the Second Amendment to the United States
2 Constitution, Section 1 of the Constitution of Kentucky declares that "All men are, by
3 nature, free and equal, and have certain inherent and inalienable rights, among which may
4 be reckoned...The right to bear arms in defense of themselves and of the State"; and
5 WHEREAS, together, the Second Amendment to the United States Constitution and
6 Section 1 of the Constitution of Kentucky guarantee the right of the people to keep and
7 bear the "arms of modern warfare" for the defense of themselves and the State. These
8 "arms" include but are not limited to the sorts of portable, bearable machine guns that
9 currently are in common use by law enforcement in this Commonwealth and military
10 units nationwide; and
11 WHEREAS, the National Firearms Act of 1934 and the Gun Control Act of 1968,
12 as amended, permit state governments to transfer machine guns to law-abiding citizens.
13 Specifically, 18 U.S.C. sec. 922(o)(2)(A) permits "a transfer to or by, or possession by or
14 under the authority of, the United States or any department or agency thereof or a State,
15 or a department, agency, or political subdivision thereof"; and
16 WHEREAS, Likewise, 18 U.S.C. sec. 925(a)(1) provides that the Gun Control Act
17 "shall not apply with respect to the transportation, shipment, receipt, possession, or
18 importation of any firearm or ammunition imported for, sold or shipped to, or issued for
19 the use of, the United States or any department or agency thereof or any State or any
20 department, agency, or political subdivision thereof"; and
21 WHEREAS, it is in the public interest of the Commonwealth of Kentucky and its
22 people that American citizens be armed and better able to assist in the defense of the
23 Commonwealth, and to resist tyranny, using bearable firearms commonly used in modern
24 warfare; and
25 WHEREAS, a well-armed American populace already has proven useful in
26 defending the homeland against foreign threats, such as when patrolling coastal areas
27 during World War II; and
Page 2 of 31
XXXX 2/25/2026 1:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 WHEREAS, it is therefore in the public interest that the Commonwealth provide a
2 means whereby machine guns may be obtained by citizens; and
3 WHEREAS, it is the intent of the General Assembly to create an Office of Public
4 Defense, which shall acquire and transfer machine guns to qualified persons;
5 NOW, THEREFORE,
6 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
7 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
8 READ AS FOLLOWS:
9 As used in Sections 1 to 10 of this Act:
10 (1) "Director" means the director of the Office of Public Defense;
11 (2) "Machine gun" means any weapon which shoots, is designed to shoot, or can be
12 readily restored to shoot, automatically more than one (1) shot, without manual
13 reloading, by a single function of the trigger;
14 (3) "Office" means the Office of Public Defense;
15 (4) "Person" means an individual, corporation, company, association, firm, trust,
16 partnership, society, or joint stock company; and
17 (5) "Qualified person" means a person who is eligible to purchase and possess
18 firearms under Kentucky and federal law.
19 SECTION 2. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
20 READ AS FOLLOWS:
21 (1) The Office of Public Defense is hereby established within the Department of
22 Kentucky State Police.
23 (2) The office shall be headed by a director who shall be, ex officio, the
24 commissioner of the Department of Kentucky State Police.
25 (3) The office shall:
26 (a) Acquire and transfer to qualified persons machine guns for the defense of
27 the Commonwealth and its people;
Page 3 of 31
XXXX 2/25/2026 1:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 (b) Prioritize to the extent practicable purchases of machine guns from
2 manufacturers and dealers located in the Commonwealth of Kentucky;
3 (c) Establish, maintain, and operate warehouses and distribution stations,
4 using existing Department of Kentucky State Police personnel,
5 infrastructure, and posts to the extent possible;
6 (d) Verify the eligibility of qualified persons to purchase machine guns through
7 the use of a background check conducted in the same manner as provided
8 in KRS 237.110(3);
9 (e) Report to the Governor annually, and at other times as the Governor may
10 require, concerning the condition, management, and financial transactions
11 of the office; and
12 (f) Do all things necessary and incidental to its powers and duties under
13 Sections 1 to 10 of this Act.
14 (4) Machine guns acquired and transferred by the office under Sections 1 to 10 of
15 this Act shall be the same as, or of like kind to, those machine guns currently in
16 use by law enforcement or the United States Armed Forces, and shall include but
17 not be limited to AR-15/M16-platform, M249-type, and MP5-type machine guns.
18 (5) The director may in his or her discretion acquire additional types of machine
19 guns beyond those identified in this section that are in common use by law
20 enforcement or the United States Armed Forces and that the director finds are
21 useful to protecting the security of a free state.
22 (6) Machine guns shall be made available for sale and transfer at each Department
23 of Kentucky State Police post.
24 SECTION 3. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
25 READ AS FOLLOWS:
26 (1) (a) Upon transfer of a machine gun to a qualified person under Sections 1 to
27 10 of this Act, the director or his or her designee shall prepare two (2)
Page 4 of 31
XXXX 2/25/2026 1:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 original copies of a signed and dated certificate bearing the seal of the
2 Commonwealth and identifying the qualified person to whom the machine
3 gun was transferred. The certificate shall identify the machine gun's make,
4 model, and serial number.
5 (b) The office shall issue one (1) copy of the certificate to the qualified person
6 and retain one (1) copy in perpetuity.
7 (c) A certificate issued under this subsection shall constitute proof of
8 compliance with Sections 1 to 10 of this Act.
9 (2) Information contained within an application, registration, or records submitted
10 or created in compliance with Sections 1 to 10 of this Act shall not be used for
11 any purpose other than to determine eligibility for, or to record, a transfer under
12 Sections 1 to 10 of this Act. The information shall be confidential and exempt
13 from disclosure under the Kentucky Open Records Act, KRS 61.870 to 61.884.
14 (3) Records associated with the transfer of a machine gun that contain personally
15 identifiable information, except for the original certificate of transfer retained by
16 the office under subsection (1)(b) of this section, shall be destroyed by the office
17 five (5) years after the transfer was made.
18 SECTION 4. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
19 READ AS FOLLOWS:
20 (1) If a qualified person to whom a machine gun has been transferred under
21 Sections 1 to 10 of this Act becomes prohibited from possessing a firearm under
22 Kentucky or federal law, the person shall return the machine gun to the office
23 within seven (7) days of learning of his or her prohibited status.
24 (2) If a responsible person of a corporation, company, association, firm, trust,
25 partnership, society, or joint stock company becomes prohibited from possessing
26 a firearm under Kentucky or federal law, but not the entity itself, the entity may
27 continue to own and possess the transferred machine gun if:
Page 5 of 31
XXXX 2/25/2026 1:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 (a) The prohibited person is no longer a responsible person of the entity; and
2 (b) The entity has at least one (1) responsible person who remains eligible to
3 possess firearms under Kentucky and federal law.
4 (3) A machine gun returned under this section shall be made available for sale to
5 other qualified persons and shall be discounted in price by a nonzero amount
6 determined by the director.
7 (4) The office shall not destroy a machine gun acquired by it pursuant to Sections 1
8 to 10 of this Act unless a machine gun returned under this section is
9 unserviceable.
10 SECTION 5. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
11 READ AS FOLLOWS:
12 (1) A qualified person may transfer a machine gun acquired under Sections 1 to 10
13 of this Act to another qualified person by presenting the machine gun to the
14 office. Upon payment of a transfer fee of two hundred seventy-five dollars ($275)
15 by the other qualified person, the office shall transfer the machine gun to the
16 other qualified person and issue a certificate to that person in accordance with
17 Section 3 of this Act.
18 (2) The transfer of a machine gun by descent or devise shall be made in the same
19 manner as in subsection (1) of this section, except a transfer fee shall not be
20 required.
21 SECTION 6. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
22 READ AS FOLLOWS:
23 (1) There is hereby established in the State Treasury a trust and agency account to be
24 known as the public defense fund. The fund shall consist of moneys received
25 from revenue generated under Sections 1 to 10 of this Act, state appropriations,
26 gifts, grants, and federal funds.
27 (2) The fund shall be administered by the director.
Page 6 of 31
XXXX 2/25/2026 1:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 (3) Amounts deposited in the fund shall be used for offsetting operational costs
2 incurred administering Sections 1 to 10 of this Act and for no other purpose.
3 (4) Fund amounts not expended at the close of a fiscal year shall lapse to the general
4 fund.
5 SECTION 7. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
6 READ AS FOLLOWS:
7 The director shall:
8 (1) Exercise general supervision of the conduct and business of the office;
9 (2) Promulgate administrative regulations in accordance with KRS Chapter 13A
10 necessary to direct and control the exercise of the powers and duties of the office;
11 and
12 (3) Expend funds from the public defense fund to offset operational costs incurred
13 administering Sections 1 to 10 of this Act.
14 SECTION 8. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
15 READ AS FOLLOWS:
16 The General Assembly hereby declares for purposes of 18 U.S.C. sec. 922(o)(2)(A)
17 that:
18 (1) All transfers of machine guns to qualified persons under Sections 1 to 10 of this
19 Act shall be deemed to have been made by and under the authority of the
20 Commonwealth of Kentucky; and
21 (2) A transferee of a machine gun under Sections 1 to 10 of this Act shall be deemed
22 to possess a machine gun that was transferred by and under the authority of the
23 Commonwealth of Kentucky.
24 SECTION 9. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
25 READ AS FOLLOWS:
26 (1) The Commonwealth, the office, the director, and officers or employees of the
27 office shall not be liable for damages sustained by any person because of an act
Page 7 of 31
XXXX 2/25/2026 1:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2302
1 or omission done in the performance of their respective duties under Sections 1 to
2 10 of this Act.
3 (2) The Commonwealth, the office, the director, and officers or employees of the
4 office shall not have criminal or civil liability for a criminal, unlawful, negligent,
5 or accidental act or omission committed by a transferee or any other person
6 related to a machine gun acquired and transferred under Sections 1 to 10 of this
7 Act.
8 SECTION 10. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 16 IS CREATED TO
9 READ AS FOLLOWS:
10 (1) The director shall add a surcharge of two hundred fifty dollars ($250) to the total
11 price of a machine gun sold and transferred under Sections 1 to 10 of this Act
12 which shall be paid into the public defense fund.
13 (2) The director may add to the price of a machine gun offered for sale to qualified
14 persons an additional surcharge to be paid into the public defense fund in an
15 amount the director determines is necessary to equal and offset the cost of
16 administration of the program created by Sections 1 to 10 of this Act but not to
17 exceed fifty dollars ($50).
18 Section 11. KRS 12.020 is amended to read as follows:
19 Departments, program cabinets and their departments, and the respective major
20 administrative bodies that they include are enumerated in this section. It is not intended
21 that this enumeration of administrative bodies be all-inclusive. Every authority, board,
22 bureau, interstate compact, commission, committee, conference, council, office, or any
23 other form of organization shall be included in or attached to the department or program
24 cabinet in which they are included or to which they are attached by statute or statutorily
25 authorized executive order; except in the case of the Personnel Board and where the
26 attached department or administrative body is headed by a constitutionally elected
27 officer, the attachment shall be solely for the purpose of dissemination of information and
